# Highway-codegen upper-bound experiment — 2026-04-27

## Question

Are the new ConvolutionHorizontal / ConvolutionVertical functions in our
iter1 patch SIMD-vectorized by GCC, or still mostly scalar? If scalar,
how much additional gain would proper highway dispatch buy us?

## Disassembly (iter3 .a, GCC 11.4, libjxl built `-march=x86-64-v2 -O3`)

Counting FP ops by width inside each function body:

| function              | scalar (`*ss`) | packed (`*ps`) | scalar fraction |
|-----------------------|---------------:|---------------:|----------------:|
| ConvolutionHorizontal |            260 |            205 |             56% |
| ConvolutionVertical   |            139 |             22 |             86% |

GCC partially auto-vectorized the H pass (it recognized the kernel-symmetric
case-N unrolls). The V pass is mostly scalar — explicit row-pointer
indexing across N input rows didn't auto-vec. So there's headroom.

## Upper-bound: force AVX2/AVX-512 codegen with __attribute__((target(...)))

(Not safe for upstream — no runtime CPU check, would crash on non-AVX-512
CPUs. Pure measurement experiment to see the ceiling.)

cpp_libjxl wall-clock, single-threaded, on top of iter1+iter2+iter3:

| size       | iter3 baseline | +AVX2 attr  | +AVX-512 attr | best Δ vs iter3 |
|------------|---------------:|------------:|--------------:|----------------:|
| 512²       |       35.3 ms  |   33.4 ms   |     32.5 ms   |          -7.9%  |
| 1280×720   |        207 ms  |    211 ms   |      199 ms   |          -3.7%  |
| 1920×1080  |        501 ms  |    487 ms   |      461 ms   |          -8.0%  |
| 3840×2160  |      2,136 ms  |  2,037 ms   |    2,066 ms   |          -4.6%  |

So a proper highway-dispatched version of these two functions buys roughly
another **4–8%** on top of iter1+iter2+iter3. Not transformative, but real.

Cumulative if highway dispatch is added (vs unpatched libjxl baseline):

| size       | unpatched | iter1+2+3 | + highway blur | total Δ |
|------------|----------:|----------:|---------------:|--------:|
| 512²       |   45.5 ms |   35.3 ms |       32.5 ms  |  -28.6% |
| 1280×720   |    256 ms |    207 ms |        199 ms  |  -22.3% |
| 1920×1080  |    590 ms |    501 ms |        461 ms  |  -21.9% |
| 3840×2160  |  2,629 ms |  2,136 ms |      2,066 ms  |  -21.4% |

## Recommendation for upstream

The PR should mention this as a known follow-up. The full highway-dispatch
refactor needs to:
1. Move ConvolutionHorizontal / ConvolutionVertical definitions into
   `HWY_NAMESPACE` (between HWY_BEFORE_NAMESPACE and HWY_AFTER_NAMESPACE).
2. Emit `HWY_EXPORT(ConvolutionHorizontal)` etc. in the HWY_ONCE block.
3. Either move `Blur()` to the HWY_ONCE block too, or forward-declare it in
   JXL_BUTTERAUGLI_ONCE and define it after HWY_EXPORT — `Blur()` calls
   `HWY_DYNAMIC_DISPATCH(ConvolutionVertical)(...)`.

Probably cleaner as a follow-up PR after iter1+2+3 lands, because (a) it's
a different concern (codegen, not algorithm) and (b) it requires moving
function definitions across the file's macro-gated regions, which is more
invasive review-wise than the current contained patch.

## Cross-arch correctness

The cache-pattern improvement (write contiguously instead of transposing)
in iter1 is arch-independent — it should at minimum match the old transpose
path on ARM/SVE/RVV/WASM. The SIMD efficiency is compiler-dependent:

- x86-64-v2 + GCC 11: 14% packed in V pass (measured).
- ARM Clang typically auto-vecs better than GCC for these structured kernels.
- SVE/RVV: predicated vectors handle this naturally.
- WASM: 4-wide SIMD, autovec depends on toolchain.

So our iter1 patch will at minimum match upstream on every arch, but to
unlock the V pass on lower-vec-quality toolchains, the highway-dispatched
follow-up is the way.

## Key disasm command for verification

```
objdump -d build/lib/libjxl-internal.a | sed -n \
  '/^[0-9a-f]\+ <_ZN3jxl19ConvolutionVerticalE/,/^$/p' \
  | grep -cE 'addss|mulss|fmadd[0-9]+ss'   # scalar count
```
